'''''Time Trek''''' is a [[History of Star Trek games#Computer|''Star Trek'' computer game]] published by [[VisiCorp|Personal Software]] in 1978.  Two similar but unrelated games were published under this brand in 1978, one for the [[Commodore PET]] by [[Brad Templeton]]<ref name=catalog/> and one programmed by Joshua Lavinsky for the [[TRS-80]] 4K Level I or Level II microcomputer.<ref name=manual/>

==Plot summary==
''Time Trek'' is a [[Real-time game|real-time]] ''[[Star Trek (1971 video game)|Star Trek]]''-style game in which the ''Enterprise'' must eliminate the Klingons before they can destroy all the starbases.<ref name="SG"/>

==Reception==
J. Mishcon reviewed ''Time Trek'' in ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' No. 28.<ref name="SG">{{cite magazine |last=Mishcon |first=J. |date=May–June 1980 |title=Time Trek |url=https://archive.org/stream/space-gamer_201601/Space_Gamer_28#page/n27/ |magazine=[[The Space Gamer]] |publisher=[[Steve Jackson Games]] |location=Austin, TX |issue=28 |department=Capsule Reviews |pages=26–27 |issn=0194-9977 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref> Mishcon commented that "the real-time aspect of the game and the aggressive tactics of the damn [[Klingon]]s make this game quite exciting. For those into hand-eye coordination and fast action, ''Time Trek'' will be enjoyable."<ref name="SG"/> In his ''80-US'' review of ''[[Space Battle (video game)|Space Battle]]'', "One of the best space war games available", Geo Blank compared the game to ''Time Trek'', commenting that "The extra control makes ''Time Trek'' a better action game."<ref name="Blank1980">{{cite magazine |last=Blank |first=Geo |date=March–April 1980 |title=Space Battle |url=https://archive.org/details/80-U.S._Volume_III_Number_2_1980-03_80-Northwest_Publishing_US/page/n70 |magazine=80-U.S. |publisher=80-Northwest Publishing Co. |location=Tacoma, WA |volume=3 |issue=2 |department=Software Reviews |page=69 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>

